# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cache-coherence-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When specific data are shared by several caches and a processor modifies the value of the shared data, the change must be propagated to all the other caches which have a copy of the data.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] This change propagation prevents the system from violating cache coherency.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The notification of data change can be done by bus snooping.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] All the snoopers monitor every transaction on a bus.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] If a transaction modifying a shared cache block appears on a bus, all the snoopers check whether their caches have the same copy of the shared block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] If a cache has a copy of the shared block, the corresponding snooper performs an action to ensure cache coherency.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The action can be a flush or an invalidation of the cache block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] It also involves a change of cache block state depending on the cache coherence protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When a processor writes on a shared cache block, all the shared copies in the other caches are invalidated through bus snooping.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] This method ensures that only one copy of a datum can be exclusively read and written by a processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] All the other copies in other caches are invalidated.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] This is the most commonly used snooping protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] MSI, MESI, MOSI, MOESI, and MESIF protocols belong to this category.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When a processor writes on a shared cache block, all the shared copies of the other caches are updated through bus snooping.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] This method broadcasts a write data to all caches throughout a bus.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] It incurs larger bus traffic than write-invalidate protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Dragon and firefly protocols belong to this category.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Each cache line is in one of the following states: "dirty" (has been updated by local processor), "valid", "invalid" or "shared".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] A cache line contains a value, and it can be read or written.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Writing on a cache line changes the value.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Each value is either in main memory (which is very slow to access), or in one or more local caches (which is fast).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When a block is first loaded into the cache, it is marked as "valid".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] On a read miss to the local cache, the read request is broadcast on the bus.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] If one has cached that address and it is in the state "dirty", it changes the state to "valid" and sends the copy to requesting node.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The "valid" state means that the cache line is current.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] On a local write miss (an attempt to write that value is made, but it's not in the cache), bus snooping ensures that any copies in other caches are set to "invalid".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] "Invalid" means that a copy used to exist in the cache, but it is no longer current.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The caching logic monitors the bus and detects if any cached memory is requested.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] If the cache is dirty and shared and there is a request on the bus for that memory, a dirty snooping element will supply the data to the requester.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] At that point either the requester can take on responsibility for the data (marking the data as dirty), or memory can grab a copy (the memory is said to have "snarfed" the data) and the two elements go to the shared state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When invalidating an address marked as dirty (i.e. one cache would have a dirty address and the other cache is writing) then the cache will ignore that request.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The new cache will be marked as dirty, valid and exclusive and that cache will now take responsibility for the address.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The advantage of using bus snooping is that it is faster than directory based coherency mechanism.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The data being shared is placed in a common directory that maintains the coherence between caches in a directory-based system.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Bus snooping is normally faster if there is enough bandwidth, because all transactions are a request/response seen by all processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The disadvantage of bus snooping is limited scalability.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Frequent snooping on a cache causes a race with an access from a processor, thus it can increase cache access time and power consumption.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Each of the requests has to be broadcast to all nodes in a system.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] It means that the size of the (physical or logical) bus and the bandwidth it provides must grow, as the system becomes larger.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Since the bus snooping does not scale well, larger cache coherent NUMA (ccNUMA) systems tend to use directory-based coherence protocols.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] When a bus transaction occurs to a specific cache block, all snoopers must snoop the bus transaction.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Then the snoopers look up their corresponding cache tag to check whether it has the same cache block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] In most cases, the caches do not have the cache block since a well optimized parallel program doesn’t share much data among threads.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Thus the cache tag lookup by the snooper is usually unnecessary work for the cache who does not have the cache block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] But the tag lookup disturbs the cache access by a processor and incurs additional power consumption.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] One way to reduce the unnecessary snooping is to use a snoop filter.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] A snoop filter determines whether a snooper needs to check its cache tag or not.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] A snoop filter is a directory-based structure and monitors all coherent traffic in order to keep track of the coherency states of cache blocks.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] It means that the snoop filter knows the caches that have a copy of a cache block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Thus it can prevent the caches that do not have the copy of a cache block from making the unnecessary snooping.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] There are three types of filters depending on the location of the snoop filters.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] One is a source filter that is located at a cache side and performs filtering before coherence traffic reaches the shared bus.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Another is a destination filter that is located at receiver caches and prevents unnecessary cache-tag look-ups at the receiver core, but this type of filtering fails to prevent the initial coherence message from the source.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] Lastly, in-network filters prune coherence traffic dynamically inside the shared bus.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The snoop filter is also categorized as inclusive and exclusive.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] The inclusive snoop filter keeps track of the presence of cache blocks in caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] However, the exclusive snoop filter monitors the absence of cache blocks in caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] In other words, a hit in the inclusive snoop filter means that the corresponding cache block is held by caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/bus-snooping] On the other hand, a hit in the exclusive snoop filter means that no cache has the requested cache block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In computer architecture, **cache coherence** is the uniformity of shared resource data that is stored in multiple local caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In a cache coherent system, if multiple clients have a cached copy of the same region of a shared memory resource, all copies are the same.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Without cache coherence, a change made to the region by one client may not be seen by others, and errors can result when the data used by different clients is mismatched.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] A cache coherence protocol is used to maintain cache coherency.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The two main types are snooping and directory-based protocols.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Cache coherence is of particular relevance in multiprocessing systems, where each CPU may have its own local cache of a shared memory resource.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In a shared memory multiprocessor system with a separate cache memory for each processor, it is possible to have many copies of shared data: one copy in the main memory and one in the local cache of each processor that requested it.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] When one of the copies of data is changed, the other copies must reflect that change.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Cache coherence is the discipline which ensures that the changes in the values of shared operands (data) are propagated throughout the system in a timely fashion.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Changes to the data in any cache must be propagated to other copies (of that cache line) in the peer caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Reads/Writes to a single memory location must be seen by all processors in the same order.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Theoretically, coherence can be performed at the load/store granularity.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] However, in practice it is generally performed at the granularity of cache blocks.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Coherence defines the behavior of reads and writes to a single address location.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In a multiprocessor system, consider that more than one processor has cached a copy of the memory location X.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In a read made by a processor P1 to location X that follows a write by another processor P2 to X, with no other writes to X made by any processor occurring between the two accesses and with the read and write being sufficiently separated, X must always return the value written by P2.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] This condition defines the concept of coherent view of memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Propagating the writes to the shared memory location ensures that all the caches have a coherent view of the memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] If processor P1 reads the old value of X, even after the write by P2, we say that the memory is incoherent.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The above conditions satisfy the **Write Propagation criteria** required for cache coherence.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] However, they are not sufficient as they do not satisfy the **Transaction Serialization condition**.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] A multi-processor system consists of four processors - P1, P2, P3 and P4, all containing cached copies of a shared variable *S* whose initial value is 0.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Processor P1 changes the value of *S* (in its cached copy) to 10 following which processor P2 changes the value of *S* in its own cached copy to 20.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] If we ensure only write propagation, then P3 and P4 will certainly see the changes made to *S* by P1 and P2.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] However, P3 may see the change made by P1 after seeing the change made by P2 and hence return 10 on a read to *S*.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] P4 on the other hand may see changes made by P1 and P2 in the order in which they are made and hence return 20 on a read to *S*.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The processors P3 and P4 now have an incoherent view of the memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The alternative definition of a coherent system is via the definition of sequential consistency memory model: "the cache coherent system must appear to execute all threads’ loads and stores to a *single* memory location in a total order that respects the program order of each thread".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Thus, the only difference between the cache coherent system and sequentially consistent system is in the number of address locations the definition talks about (single memory location for a cache coherent system, and all memory locations for a sequentially consistent system).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Another definition is: "a multiprocessor is cache consistent if all writes to the same memory location are performed in some sequential order".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Rarely, but especially in algorithms, coherence can instead refer to the locality of reference.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Multiple copies of the same data can exist in different cache simultaneously and if processors are allowed to update their own copies freely, an inconsistent view of memory can result.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The two most common mechanisms of ensuring coherency are *snooping* and *directory-based*, each having their own benefits and drawbacks.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Snooping based protocols tend to be faster, if enough bandwidth is available, since all transactions are a request/response seen by all processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The drawback is that snooping isn't scalable.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Every request must be broadcast to all nodes in a system, meaning that as the system gets larger, the size of the (logical or physical) bus and the bandwidth it provides must grow.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Directories, on the other hand, tend to have longer latency (with a 3 hop request-forward-respond) but use much less bandwidth since messages are point to point and not broadcast.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] For this reason, many of the larger systems (>64 processors) use this type of cache coherence.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] snooping is a process where the individual caches monitor address lines for accesses to memory locations that they have cached.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] For the snooping mechanism, a snoop filter reduces the snooping traffic by maintaining a plurality of entries, each representing a cache line that may be owned by one or more nodes.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] When replacement of one of the entries is required, the snoop filter selects for the replacement of the entry representing the cache line or lines owned by the fewest nodes, as determined from a presence vector in each of the entries.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] A temporal or other type of algorithm is used to refine the selection if more than one cache line is owned by the fewest nodes.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In a directory-based system, the data being shared is placed in a common directory that maintains the coherence between caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The directory acts as a filter through which the processor must ask permission to load an entry from the primary memory to its cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] When an entry is changed, the directory either updates or invalidates the other caches with that entry.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Distributed shared memory systems mimic these mechanisms in an attempt to maintain consistency between blocks of memory in loosely coupled systems.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Coherence protocols apply cache coherence in multiprocessor systems.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The intention is that two clients must never see different values for the same shared data.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The protocol must implement the basic requirements for coherence.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] It can be tailor-made for the target system or application.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Protocols can also be classified as snoopy or directory-based.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Typically, early systems used directory-based protocols where a directory would keep a track of the data being shared and the sharers.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In snoopy protocols, the transaction requests (to read, write, or upgrade) are sent out to all processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] All processors snoop the request and respond appropriately.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] When a write operation is observed to a location that a cache has a copy of, the cache controller invalidates its own copy of the snooped memory location, which forces a read from main memory of the new value on its next access.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] When a write operation is observed to a location that a cache has a copy of, the cache controller updates its own copy of the snooped memory location with the new data.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] If the protocol design states that whenever any copy of the shared data is changed, all the other copies must be "updated" to reflect the change, then it is a write-update protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] If the design states that a write to a cached copy by any processor requires other processors to discard or invalidate their cached copies, then it is a write-invalidate protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] However, scalability is one shortcoming of broadcast protocols.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] Various models and protocols have been devised for maintaining coherence, such as MSI, MESI (aka Illinois), MOSI, MOESI, MERSI, MESIF, write-once, Synapse, Berkeley, Firefly and Dragon protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] In 2011, ARM Ltd proposed the AMBA 4 ACE for handling coherency in SoCs.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/cache-coherence] The AMBA CHI (Coherent Hub Interface) specification from ARM Ltd, which belongs to AMBA5 group of specifications defines the interfaces for the connection of fully coherent processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In computer engineering, **directory-based cache coherence** is a type of cache coherence mechanism, where directories are used to manage caches in place of bus snooping.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Bus snooping methods scale poorly due to the use of broadcasting.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] These methods can be used to target both performance and scalability of directory systems.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In the full bit vector format, for each possible cache line in memory, a bit is used to track whether every individual processor has that line stored in its cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The full bit vector format is the simplest structure to implement, but the least scalable.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The SGI Origin 2000 uses a combination of full bit vector and coarse bit vector depending on the number of processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Each directory entry must have 1 bit stored per processor per cache line, along with bits for tracking the state of the directory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] This leads to the total size required being *(number of processors)×number of cache lines*, having a storage overhead ratio of *(number of processors)/(cache block size×8)*.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] It can be observed that directory overhead scales linearly with the number of processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] While this may be fine for a small number of processors, when implemented in large systems the size requirements for the directory becomes excessive.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] For example, with a block size of 32 bytes and 1024 processors, the storage overhead ratio becomes 1024/(32×8) = 400%.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The coarse bit vector format has a similar structure to the full bit vector format, though rather than tracking one bit per processor for every cache line, the directory groups several processors into nodes, storing whether a cache line is stored in a node rather than a processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] This improves size requirements at the expense of bus traffic saving (processors per node - 1)×(total lines) bits of space.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Thus the ratio overhead is the same, just replacing number of processors with number of processor groups.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] When a bus request is made for a cache line that one processor in the group has, the directory broadcasts the signal into every processor in the node rather than just the caches that contain it, leading to unnecessary traffic to nodes that do not have the data cached.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In this case the directory entry uses 1 bit for a group of processors for each cache line.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] For the same example as Full Bit Vector format if we consider 1 bit for 8 processors as a group, then the storage overhead will be 128/(32×8)=50%.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] This is a significant improvement over the Full Bit Vector format.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] A cache only stores a small subset of blocks in main memory at a particular time.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Hence most of the entries in the directory will belong to uncached blocks.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In the sparse directory format the wastage is reduced by storing only the cached blocks in the directory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Consider a processor with a cache size of 64KB with a block size of 32 bytes and the main memory size to be 4MB.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The maximum number of entries that the directory can have in the sparse directory format is 2048.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] If the directory has an entry for all the blocks in the memory the number of entries in the directory will be 131072.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Thus it is evident that the storage improvement provided by sparse directory format is very significant.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In this format the directory is decentralised and distributed among the caches that share a memory block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Different caches that share a memory block are arranged in the form of a binary tree.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The cache that accesses a memory block first is the root node.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Each memory block has the root node information (HEAD) and Sharing counter field (SC).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The SC field has the number of caches that share the block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Each cache entry has pointers to the next sharing caches known as L-CHD and R-CHD.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] A condition for this directory is that the binary tree should be number balanced, i.e. the number of nodes in the left sub tree must be equal to or one greater than the number of nodes in the right subtree.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] All the subtrees should also be number balanced.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In this format the memory holds the directory pointer to the latest cache that accessed the block and each cache has the pointer to the previous cache that accessed the block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] So when a processor sends a write request to a block in memory, the processor sends invalidations down the chain of pointers.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In this directory when a cache block is replaced we need to traverse the list in order to change the directory which increases latency.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] In order to prevent this doubly linked lists are widely used now in which each cached copy has pointers to previous and the next cache that accesses the block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] The limited pointer format uses a set number of pointers to track the processors that are caching the data.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] When a new processor caches a block, a free pointer is chosen from a pool to point to that processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] There are a few options for handling cases when the number of sharers exceeds the number of free pointers.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] One method is to invalidate one of the sharers, using its pointer for the new requestor, though this can be costly in cases where a block has a large number of readers, such as a lock.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] Another method is to have a separate pool of free pointers available to all the blocks.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/directory-based-cache-coherence] This method is usually effective as the number of blocks shared by a large number of processors is not normally very large.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In computing, a **memory barrier**, also known as a **membar**, **memory fence** or **fence instruction**, is a type of barrier instruction that causes a central processing unit (CPU) or compiler to enforce an ordering constraint on memory operations issued before and after the barrier instruction.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] This typically means that operations issued prior to the barrier are guaranteed to be performed before operations issued after the barrier.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are necessary because most modern CPUs employ performance optimizations that can result in out-of-order execution.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] This reordering of memory operations (loads and stores) normally goes unnoticed within a single thread of execution, but can cause unpredictable behavior in concurrent programs and device drivers unless carefully controlled.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The exact nature of an ordering constraint is hardware dependent and defined by the architecture's memory ordering model.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Some architectures provide multiple barriers for enforcing different ordering constraints.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are typically used when implementing low-level machine code that operates on memory shared by multiple devices.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Such code includes synchronization primitives and lock-free data structures on multiprocessor systems, and device drivers that communicate with computer hardware.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] When a program runs on a single-CPU machine, the hardware performs the necessary bookkeeping to ensure that the program executes as if all memory operations were performed in the order specified by the programmer (program order), so memory barriers are not necessary.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] However, when the memory is shared with multiple devices, such as other CPUs in a multiprocessor system, or memory-mapped peripherals, out-of-order access may affect program behavior.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] For example, a second CPU may see memory changes made by the first CPU in a sequence that differs from program order.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] A program is run via a process which can be multi-threaded (i.e. a software thread such as pthreads as opposed to a hardware thread).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Different processes do not share a memory space so this discussion does not apply to two programs, each one running in a different process (hence a different memory space).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] It applies to two or more (software) threads running in a single process (i.e. a single memory space where multiple software threads share a single memory space).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Multiple software threads, within a single process, may run concurrently on a multi-core processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Initially, memory locations x and f both hold the value 0.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #1 loops while the value of f is zero, then it prints the value of x.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #2 stores the value 42 into x and then stores the value 1 into f.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Pseudo-code for the two program fragments is shown below.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The steps of the program correspond to individual processor instructions.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] One might expect the print statement to always print the number "42"; however, if thread #2's store operations are executed out-of-order, it is possible for f to be updated *before* x, and the print statement might therefore print "0".
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Similarly, thread #1's load operations may be executed out-of-order and it is possible for x to be read *before* f is checked, and again the print statement might therefore print an unexpected value.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] For most programs neither of these situations is acceptable.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] A memory barrier must be inserted before thread #2's assignment to f to ensure that the new value of x is visible to other processors at or prior to the change in the value of f.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Another important point is a memory barrier must also be inserted before thread #1's access to x to ensure the value of x is not read prior to seeing the change in the value of f.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] If the processor's store operations are executed out-of-order, the hardware module may be triggered before data is ready in memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] For another illustrative example (a non-trivial one that arises in actual practice), see double-checked locking.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In the case of the ARM architecture family, the DMB, DSB and ISB instructions are used.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In the case of the RISC-V architecture, the FENCE instruction is used.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In the case of the x86 architecture, the MFENCE, LFENCE, and SFENCE instructions are used.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Multithreaded programs usually use synchronization primitives provided by a high-level programming environment—such as Java or .NET—or an application programming interface (API) such as POSIX Threads or Windows API.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes and semaphores are provided to synchronize access to resources from parallel threads of execution.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] These primitives are usually implemented with the memory barriers required to provide the expected memory visibility semantics.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In such environments explicit use of memory barriers is not generally necessary.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Memory barrier instructions address reordering effects only at the hardware level.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Compilers may also reorder instructions as part of the program optimization process.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Although the effects on parallel program behavior can be similar in both cases, in general, it is necessary to take separate measures to inhibit compiler reordering optimizations for data that may be shared by multiple threads of execution.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] In C and C++, the volatile keyword was intended to allow C and C++ programs to directly access memory-mapped I/O.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Memory-mapped I/O generally requires that the reads and writes specified in source code happen in the exact order specified with no omissions.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Omissions or reorderings of reads and writes by the compiler would break the communication between the program and the device accessed by memory-mapped I/O.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] A C or C++ compiler may not omit reads from and writes to volatile memory locations, nor may it reorder read/writes relative to other such actions for the same volatile location (variable).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The keyword volatile *does not guarantee a memory barrier* to enforce cache-consistency.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] Therefore, the use of volatile alone is not sufficient to use a variable for inter-thread communication on all systems and processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/memory-barrier] The C and C++ standards prior to C11 and C++11 do not address multiple threads (or multiple processors), and as such, the usefulness of volatile depends on the compiler and hardware.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The **MESI protocol** is an invalidate-based cache coherence protocol, and is one of the most common protocols that support write-back caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] It is also known as the **Illinois protocol** due to its development at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Write back caches can save considerable bandwidth generally wasted on a write through cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] There is always a dirty state present in write-back caches that indicates that the data in the cache is different from that in the main memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The Illinois Protocol requires a cache-to-cache transfer on a miss if the block resides in another cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This protocol reduces the number of main memory transactions with respect to the MSI protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This marks a significant improvement in performance.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The cache is required to write the data back to the main memory at some time in the future, before permitting any other read of the (no longer valid) main memory state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The write-back changes the line to the Shared state (S).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Indicates that this cache line is invalid (unused).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] When the block is marked M (modified) or E (exclusive), the copies of the block in other Caches are marked as I (Invalid).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The MESI protocol is defined by a finite-state machine that transitions from one state to another based on 2 stimuli.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The first stimulus is the processor-specific Read and Write request.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] For example: A processor P1 has a Block X in its Cache, and there is a request from the processor to read or write from that block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The second stimulus is given through the bus connecting the processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] In particular, the "Bus side requests" come from other processors that don't have the cache block or the updated data in their Cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The bus requests are monitored with the help of Snoopers, which monitor all the bus transactions.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] BusUpgr: Snooped request that indicates that there is a write request to a Cache block requested by another processor that already has that **cache block residing in its own cache**.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Flush: Snooped request that indicates that an entire cache block is written back to the main memory by another processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] FlushOpt: Snooped request that indicates that an entire cache block is posted on the bus in order to supply it to another processor (Cache to Cache transfers).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The snooping function on the memory side is done by the Memory controller.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Each Cache block has its own 4 state finite-state machine (refer image 1.1).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A write may only be performed freely if the cache line is in the Modified or Exclusive state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] If it is in the Shared state, all other cached copies must be invalidated first.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This is typically done by a broadcast operation known as *Request For Ownership (RFO)*.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A cache that holds a line in the Modified state must *snoop* (intercept) all attempted reads (from all the other caches in the system) of the corresponding main memory location and insert the data that it holds.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This can be done by forcing the read to *back off* (i.e. retry later), then writing the data to main memory and changing the cache line to the Shared state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] It can also be done by sending data from Modified cache to the cache performing the read.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Note, snooping only required for read misses (protocol ensures that Modified cannot exist if any other cache can perform a read hit).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A cache that holds a line in the Shared state must listen for invalidate or request-for-ownership broadcasts from other caches, and discard the line (by moving it into Invalid state) on a match.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The Modified and Exclusive states are always precise: i.e. they match the true cache line ownership situation in the system.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The Shared state may be imprecise: if another cache discards a Shared line, this cache may become the sole owner of that cache line, but it will not be promoted to Exclusive state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Other caches do not broadcast notices when they discard cache lines, and this cache could not use such notifications without maintaining a count of the number of shared copies.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] In that sense the Exclusive state is an opportunistic optimization: If the CPU wants to modify a cache line in state S, a bus transaction is necessary to invalidate all other cached copies.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] State E enables modifying a cache line with no bus transaction.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] For example, let us assume that the following stream of read/write references.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] All the references are to the same location and the digit refers to the processor issuing the reference.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Initially it is assumed that all the caches are empty.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A *Read For Ownership (RFO)* is an operation in cache coherency protocols that combines a read and an invalidate broadcast.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The operation is issued by a processor trying to write into a cache line that is in the shared (S) or invalid (I) states of the MESI protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The operation causes all other caches to set the state of such a line to I.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A read for ownership transaction is a read operation with intent to write to that memory address.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] It brings data to the cache and invalidates all other processor caches that hold this memory line.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This is termed "BusRdX" in tables above.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] MESI in its naive, straightforward implementation exhibits two particular performance issues.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] First, when writing to an invalid cache line, there is a long delay while the line is fetched from other CPUs.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Second, moving cache lines to the invalid state is time-consuming.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] To mitigate these delays, CPUs implement store buffers and invalidate queues.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A store buffer is used when writing to an invalid cache line.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] As the write will proceed anyway, the CPU issues a read-invalid message (hence the cache line in question and all other CPUs' cache lines that store that memory address are invalidated) and then pushes the write into the store buffer, to be executed when the cache line finally arrives in the cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A direct consequence of the store buffer's existence is that when a CPU commits a write, that write is not immediately written in the cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Note that while a CPU can read its own previous writes in its store buffer, other CPUs *cannot see those writes* until they are flushed to the cache — a CPU cannot scan the store buffer of other CPUs.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] With regard to invalidation messages, CPUs implement invalidate queues, whereby incoming invalidate requests are instantly acknowledged but not immediately acted upon.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Instead, invalidation messages simply enter an invalidation queue and their processing occurs as soon as possible (but not necessarily instantly).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Consequently, a CPU can be oblivious to the fact that a cache line in its cache is actually invalid, as the invalidation queue contains invalidations that have been received but haven't yet been applied.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Note that, unlike the store buffer, the CPU can't scan the invalidation queue, as that CPU and the invalidation queue are physically located on opposite sides of the cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] As a result, memory barriers are required.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A *store barrier* will flush the store buffer, ensuring all writes have been applied to that CPU's cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] A *read barrier* will flush the invalidation queue, thus ensuring that all writes by other CPUs become visible to the flushing CPU.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Furthermore, memory management units do not scan the store buffer, causing similar problems.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This effect is visible even in single threaded processors.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The most striking difference between MESI and MSI is the extra "exclusive" state present in the MESI protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This extra state was added as it has many advantages.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] When a processor needs to read a block that **none of the other processors have** and then write to it, two bus transactions will take place in the case of MSI.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] First, a BusRd request is issued to read the block followed by a BusUpgr request before writing to the block.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The BusUpgr request in this scenario is useless as none of the other caches have the same block, but there is no way for one cache to know about this.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Thus, MESI protocol overcomes this limitation by adding an Exclusive state, which results in saving a bus request.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This makes a huge difference when a sequential application is running.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] As only one processor works on a piece of data, all the accesses will be exclusive.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] MSI performs much worse in this case due to the extra bus messages.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Even in the case of a highly parallel application with minimal sharing of data, MESI is far faster.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Adding the Exclusive state also comes at no cost as 3 states and 4 states are both representable with 2 bits.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] In case continuous read and write operations are performed by various caches on a particular block, the data has to be flushed to the bus every time.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] Thus, the main memory will pull this on every flush and remain in a clean state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] But this is not a requirement and is just an additional overhead caused by using MESI.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] This challenge was overcome by the MOESI protocol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] In case of S (Shared State), multiple snoopers may response with FlushOpt with the same data (see the example above).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/mesi-protocol] The F state in MESIF addresses this redundancy.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] In order for this to be possible, direct cache-to-cache transfers of data must be possible, so a cache with the data in the modified state can supply that data to another reader without transferring it to memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] As discussed in AMD64 Architecture Programmer's Manual Vol.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This cache has the only valid copy of the cache line, and has made changes to that copy.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] The cached copy may be further modified freely.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This line is one of several copies in the system.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] the line is modified (dirty) relative to main memory, and this cache has the exclusive responsibility for ensuring main memory is eventually updated.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] request with data, to ensure the stale copy in main memory is not used.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This cache has the only copy of the line, but the line is clean (unmodified).
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] It may be written to, changing to the Modified state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This cache does not have permission to modify the copy.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] be dirty with respect to memory; if it is, one cache has a copy in the Owned state, and that cache is responsible for eventually updating main memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] If no cache holds the line in the Owned state, the memory copy is up to date.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] The cache line may not be written, but must be changed to the Exclusive or Modified state first, by invalidating all other cached copies.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] (If the cache line was Owned before, the invalidate response will indicate this, and the state will become Modified, so the obligation to eventually write the data back to memory is not forgotten.) It may also be discarded (changed to the Invalid state) at any time.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This block is not valid; it must be fetched to satisfy any attempted access.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This protocol, a more elaborate version of the simpler MESI protocol, avoids the need to write a dirty cache line back to main memory when another processor tries to read it.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] Instead, the Owned state allows a processor to supply the modified data directly to the other processor.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This is beneficial when the communication between two CPUs is significantly better than to main memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] An example would be multi-core CPUs with per-core L2 caches.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] While MOESI can quickly share dirty cache lines from cache, it may struggle to quickly share clean lines from cache.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] If a cache line is clean with respect to memory and in the shared state, then there is no obvious single candidate cache to respond to a read request, so it is normal to let the read request be filled from memory.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] If a processor wishes to write to an Owned cache line, it must notify the other processors which are sharing that cache line.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] The standard implementation simply tells them to invalidate their copies, moving its own copy to the Modified state when this is complete, but alternatively it may use a write-through policy, telling them to update their copies with the new contents.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] This is a partial write-through which does not go as far as main memory; the processor's own copy remains in the Owned state.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] The latter reduces cache traffic *if* there are multiple active readers of e.g. a heavily contended lock; one broadcast write is less communication than separate replies to a thundering herd of read requests.
[src:cache-coherence-protocol/moesi-protocol] Because these two variants are fully compatible, they may both be used in the same system based on heuristics like the cache's estimate of the number of active readers of this cache line.
